(## 6. Key Features Explained in Interview Language) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 6.1 Domain and service detection) Tj
T*
(Raw packet traffic often only provides IPs and ports. To make the output meaningful, I added a) Tj
T*
(detection layer that extracts hostnames from:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- DNS question names) Tj
T*
(- HTTP Host headers) Tj
T*
(- TLS SNI in client hello packets) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Then I map those hostnames into service names like:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- YouTube) Tj
T*
(- Instagram) Tj
T*
(- Facebook/Meta) Tj
T*
(- Google) Tj
T*
(- GitHub) Tj
T*
(- LinkedIn) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This makes the UI much more understandable than showing only ports and IPs.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 6.2 Decision engine) Tj
T*
(The system classifies packets into three categories:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- `ALLOWED`) Tj
T*
(- `BLOCKED`) Tj
T*
(- `REVIEW`) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The classification is based on:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- TCP resets) Tj
T*
(- ICMP unreachable packets) Tj
T*
(- policy-blocked ports) Tj
T*
(- imported firewall `DROP` evidence) Tj
T*
(- unsupported or ambiguous traffic being marked as `REVIEW`) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This gives a simple but explainable network-decision model.) Tj
T*
ET
endstream
endobj
